WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:00.720
Good afternoon.

2
00:00:01.620 --> 00:00:03.900
Welcome to the Meet the Expert session with

3
00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:14.820
Maria Blasco: Targeting Telomeres in Cancer and Aging.

4
00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:17.860
As you may know, Maria is

5
00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:23.240
one of the leaders in telomere biology, and she's going

6
00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:26.980
to be telling us about her latest research. Thank you so much.

7
00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:28.660
And you can pose your questions.

8
00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:33.940
You can either use the QR code to enter your questions online,

9
00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:37.980
but also you can, after the talk, ask your questions in

10
00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:39.540
the microphone. Thank you.

11
00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:49.720
Hi, good afternoon. So it's a pleasure for me to tell you

12
00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:53.080
about the work we are doing on the role of telomeres in cancer and aging.

13
00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:57.460
So I will start telling you about the role of telomeres in aging,

14
00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:01.000
because as you know, aging is the highest risk factor also for cancer.

15
00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:05.500
And then I will tell you about the work we are doing with trying to target

16
00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:09.480
telomeres in cancer. So as you know, aging is

17
00:01:09.540 --> 00:01:12.180
the cause of many of the diseases that kill us.

18
00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:15.480
Among these diseases are diseases like cancer,

19
00:01:15.980 --> 00:01:19.470
or I highlighted fibrosis because I will be telling

20
00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:23.360
about the role of telomeres in fibrosis, and fibrosis is also a

21
00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:24.950
risk factor for cancer,

22
00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:28.539
like in the case of liver, lung fibrosis.

23
00:01:29.180 --> 00:01:29.440
So

24
00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:34.300
we think that the causes of aging have the key to

25
00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:36.180
understand all of these diseases.

26
00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:40.320
They can be influenced by the genes, but also by the habits.

27
00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:44.620
And understanding these causes of aging will allow us to have biomarkers

28
00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:48.740
for early detection of these diseases, but

29
00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:52.600
also we will be able maybe to prevent the appearance of these

30
00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.600
diseases by delaying aging, and also to have

31
00:01:57.660 --> 00:02:01.360
better and more effective treatments for the diseases associated with aging, and I

32
00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:05.240
include here also cancer. So which are these causes

33
00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:05.780
of aging?

34
00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:07.280
So,

35
00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:12.180
there are several very well-characterized molecular pathways that have been

36
00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:15.780
demonstrated to be important for aging, and one of them is the telomere

37
00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:16.420
shortening.

38
00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:21.360
Telomere shortening associated to cell division due to the end replication problem.

39
00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:22.140
And

40
00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:25.660
telomere shortening, in turn, has been

41
00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:30.440
defined as a primary cause of aging because it leads to other causes of aging,

42
00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:34.380
like genomic instability, for instance, which is also underlying cancer

43
00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:36.960
risk, stem cell exhaustion, et cetera.

44
00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:41.080
Recently, we have updated this review by including other hallmarks

45
00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:45.020
of aging. But again, telomere shortening is one of the primary causes

46
00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:45.600
of aging.

47
00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:51.460
Telomeres, however, have to be maintained somehow,

48
00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:55.620
because if not, it would be impossible to maintain the species, or it would be

49
00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:57.540
impossible for cancer cells to divide.

50
00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:02.160
And in fact, there is an activity called telomerase that is able to re-elongate

51
00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:05.780
telomeres. So telomerase is able to elongate telomeres, and this is what

52
00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:09.310
allows the maintenance of different generations in the species.

53
00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:14.410
When we are born, telomerase is silenced, and this leads to telomere shortening.

54
00:03:15.210 --> 00:03:18.890
Telomere shortening has been demonstrated to lead to age-related

55
00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:22.700
diseases. And there is the case of the so-called telomere

56
00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:26.440
biology diseases. These are people that have mutations in telomerase, and they are

57
00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:30.380
going to develop prematurely a number of diseases, including,

58
00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:33.780
as I said before, different types of fibrosis.

59
00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:38.049
Cancer is also a disease associated to short telomeres,

60
00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:40.020
which lead to chromosomal instability.

61
00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:44.460
But in the case of cancer cells, they escape this mortality

62
00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:47.840
produced by short telomeres by activating telomerase,

63
00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:51.920
which is one of the most mutated genes in cancer, actually.

64
00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:56.540
And telomere length has been proposed to be a biomarker for this

65
00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:00.200
aging of our cells and tissues.

66
00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:02.160
So we know that

67
00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:06.840
if you induce telomere shortening, this is sufficient to induce aging.

68
00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:10.760
But my lab also demonstrated that if you make mice with

69
00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.930
longer telomeres, and in this case, we did it by

70
00:04:13.980 --> 00:04:17.921
overexpressing the telomerase catalytic subunit, the

71
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:18.680
TERT gene,

72
00:04:19.620 --> 00:04:22.041
they can live more and have also less cancer.

73
00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:22.400
So,

74
00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:26.400
having longer telomeres in mice, at least,

75
00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:29.860
we show here that it protected from cancer.

76
00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:33.820
More recently, we have shown the same by using a telomerase

77
00:04:33.960 --> 00:04:36.320
activation strategy, a telomerase gene therapy.

78
00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:41.000
We show that if we treated mice with telomerase, this delay many

79
00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:43.060
diseases of aging, including cancer.

80
00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:46.740
So again, showing that maintaining telomeres

81
00:04:47.540 --> 00:04:51.520
was protecting from cancer. And in fact, we didn't see

82
00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:55.320
any deleterious effects of activating telomerase in this

83
00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:58.080
experiment because, in fact, the mice lived longer,

84
00:04:58.960 --> 00:04:59.920
both the

85
00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:04.500
group that was treated at the middle age, one year old, and a group

86
00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:07.420
treated at an old age, two years old.

87
00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:13.120
This would open the question, why don't we have longer telomeres then if

88
00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:14.260
long telomeres are not

89
00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:20.280
apparently bad? So we try to address this question

90
00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:24.160
by doing an epigenetic trick in mice

91
00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:28.080
again. We know that telomerase is activated in the inner cell mass,

92
00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:32.280
and we also know that ES cells and iPS cells, they have high

93
00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:33.900
levels of telomerase. My group

94
00:05:35.180 --> 00:05:39.100
show, discovered by chance, that if you maintain pluripotent

95
00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:42.520
cells in vitro, dividing, telomeres keep growing

96
00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:46.360
beyond the natural length of the inner cell mass of the

97
00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:50.460
species. And in this way, we generated ES cells that we call

98
00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:54.580
with ultra-long telomeres, much longer telomeres than normal.

99
00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:55.700
And we have used this

100
00:05:57.140 --> 00:05:59.880
trick to generate chimeric mice that

101
00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:04.400
are born with much longer telomeres than normal without altering the

102
00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:08.308
telomerase gene or any other gene.So you can see here what we

103
00:06:08.928 --> 00:06:12.628
did was we took a cell modular, we aggregated ES cells with

104
00:06:12.888 --> 00:06:16.788
ultra long or normal telomeres. In this case, you can see the ultra

105
00:06:16.808 --> 00:06:19.448
long telomeres. We are going to see them in green

106
00:06:20.508 --> 00:06:24.368
color, expressing the GFP. And then we generated chimeric mice.

107
00:06:24.428 --> 00:06:28.248
So this is the eye of one of these chimeric mice, and you can

108
00:06:28.328 --> 00:06:32.168
see the telomeres in red color, and you can see areas of the eye which much

109
00:06:32.248 --> 00:06:36.048
longer telomeres than natural. So these mice have very long telomeres,

110
00:06:36.168 --> 00:06:37.788
double the length of a normal mouse.

111
00:06:38.208 --> 00:06:41.668
The question is, are they going to have more cancer, less cancer, live longer?

112
00:06:42.948 --> 00:06:46.888
And we see that they live longer. So, this we expect because telomeres

113
00:06:46.898 --> 00:06:50.808
start off with a longer length, even though the

114
00:06:50.848 --> 00:06:54.588
telomere shortening is the same as in normal mice, and they are also cancer

115
00:06:54.668 --> 00:06:58.388
protected. Even when we induce chemical carcinogenesis in these

116
00:06:58.448 --> 00:07:01.548
mice, they have less cancer. We have also done this with

117
00:07:01.608 --> 00:07:05.448
100% chimeras, so all the cells of the mouse

118
00:07:05.768 --> 00:07:08.848
have ultra long telomeres, and they are also cancer protected.

119
00:07:08.908 --> 00:07:09.128
So

120
00:07:10.448 --> 00:07:14.348
long telomeres or longer telomeres than normal in a mouse at least are

121
00:07:14.428 --> 00:07:17.708
not leading to more cancer. They are delaying

122
00:07:18.848 --> 00:07:20.608
aging and also delaying cancer.

123
00:07:22.228 --> 00:07:26.108
So what we have been doing regarding the role of telomeres in aging is to try

124
00:07:26.188 --> 00:07:29.768
to use this telomerase gene therapy to show whether it's

125
00:07:29.828 --> 00:07:31.248
effective for the treatment

126
00:07:32.108 --> 00:07:35.888
of different age-related diseases, as well as these telomere biology

127
00:07:35.928 --> 00:07:39.488
syndromes. So we have shown that telomerase gene

128
00:07:39.568 --> 00:07:43.248
therapy has a therapeutic effect in cardiovascular

129
00:07:43.648 --> 00:07:45.428
disease, in particular in heart infarct.

130
00:07:45.988 --> 00:07:49.948
We have also shown therapeutic effects in mouse models of aplastic anemia

131
00:07:49.958 --> 00:07:53.548
associated to short telomeres and pulmonary

132
00:07:53.568 --> 00:07:57.308
and kidney fibrosis. I will be showing you that because, as I said,

133
00:07:57.368 --> 00:08:01.308
fibrosis, I think, is also very interesting for cancer because it's also at the

134
00:08:01.388 --> 00:08:03.068
origin of cancer.

135
00:08:04.348 --> 00:08:04.728
So

136
00:08:05.808 --> 00:08:09.648
these telomere biology diseases, many of them are characterized by this

137
00:08:09.788 --> 00:08:13.108
fibrosis, which is also a risk factor for cancer.

138
00:08:13.968 --> 00:08:17.928
And our model, in the case of pulmonary fibrosis, was

139
00:08:17.967 --> 00:08:21.548
the first telomere biology disease to be shown to be

140
00:08:21.608 --> 00:08:25.488
associated to dysfunctional telomeres, is that these short

141
00:08:25.498 --> 00:08:26.428
telomeres probably

142
00:08:27.348 --> 00:08:31.188
synergize with damaging agents to the lung, like smoking

143
00:08:31.768 --> 00:08:33.308
or pollution. And

144
00:08:34.489 --> 00:08:38.428
when the telomeres are short, the regenerative compartment of the

145
00:08:38.489 --> 00:08:42.408
lung cannot regenerate. We have shown that short telomeres impede

146
00:08:42.889 --> 00:08:46.728
stem cell mobilization, and when you don't have regeneration, you have immune

147
00:08:46.768 --> 00:08:50.028
response and fibrosis. And the current treatments

148
00:08:50.108 --> 00:08:52.108
actually are not curing the patients.

149
00:08:52.228 --> 00:08:55.757
They are tackling fibrosis, but they are not

150
00:08:55.888 --> 00:08:59.428
curative, and we think it's because you still have the cause there.

151
00:08:59.468 --> 00:09:03.388
In the case of at least a third of the

152
00:09:03.428 --> 00:09:07.188
cases of pulmonary fibrosis are suspected to be associated to

153
00:09:07.208 --> 00:09:08.068
short telomeres.

154
00:09:08.988 --> 00:09:11.408
This is in addition to the familial cases.

155
00:09:12.048 --> 00:09:14.588
And if you have short telomeres, it impedes regeneration.

156
00:09:14.688 --> 00:09:18.488
So we first try to identify which is the cell type

157
00:09:18.708 --> 00:09:21.288
of origin of fibrosis associated to short telomeres.

158
00:09:21.528 --> 00:09:25.408
And for that, what we did in collaboration with AstraZeneca in the

159
00:09:25.448 --> 00:09:29.408
US, we induced telomere dysfunction in different cell types

160
00:09:29.468 --> 00:09:29.948
of the lung

161
00:09:31.568 --> 00:09:33.888
by deleting one of the telomere binding proteins.

162
00:09:34.088 --> 00:09:37.828
And we saw that only when we induced telomere dysfunction in the

163
00:09:37.888 --> 00:09:41.448
alveolar type two cells, so the cell types that we studied,

164
00:09:41.868 --> 00:09:42.308
we have

165
00:09:43.188 --> 00:09:45.668
interstitial fibrosis similar to the human disease.

166
00:09:46.148 --> 00:09:49.588
But this does not happen when we induce telomere dysfunction in fibroblasts

167
00:09:50.388 --> 00:09:53.668
or in the basal cells or in the club cells.

168
00:09:53.888 --> 00:09:57.348
So this is pointing to these 82 cells are the cells we would

169
00:09:58.188 --> 00:10:02.028
want to target in order to treat pulmonary fibrosis associated with

170
00:10:02.088 --> 00:10:02.728
short telomeres.

171
00:10:03.528 --> 00:10:05.338
In mouse models, we have shown that

172
00:10:06.308 --> 00:10:10.248
this telomerase gene therapy can target these 82

173
00:10:10.288 --> 00:10:11.458
cells, and we can

174
00:10:15.128 --> 00:10:18.408
slow down or reverse fibrosis induced by

175
00:10:19.408 --> 00:10:20.188
short telomeres.

176
00:10:21.788 --> 00:10:21.988
And

177
00:10:22.888 --> 00:10:26.608
at the molecular level, we see that we isolate the 82

178
00:10:26.688 --> 00:10:30.588
cells of these mice. They express telomerase, and

179
00:10:30.648 --> 00:10:33.728
they rescue DNA damage and immune signaling pathways.

180
00:10:34.168 --> 00:10:37.128
And this is why we have this therapeutic effect

181
00:10:38.428 --> 00:10:41.748
in the lung fibrosis model. It's a lung fibrosis model induced

182
00:10:42.208 --> 00:10:46.048
by short telomeres and a low dose of bleomycin that does

183
00:10:46.068 --> 00:10:48.228
not induce fibrosis in a wild-type mouse.

184
00:10:48.288 --> 00:10:48.448
So

185
00:10:49.328 --> 00:10:53.308
short telomeres are in the origin of the disease in this mouse model.

186
00:10:53.568 --> 00:10:56.848
It's like a humanized mouse model of pulmonary fibrosis.

187
00:10:58.628 --> 00:11:02.448
So the question is: Well, maybe we can cure fibrosis, but

188
00:11:02.788 --> 00:11:06.508
are we going to induce cancer because I told you before that cancer

189
00:11:06.528 --> 00:11:09.388
cells need to activate telomerase in order to divide indefinitely.

190
00:11:10.108 --> 00:11:14.008
And we did this safety experiment in which at the same time or

191
00:11:14.028 --> 00:11:17.428
before we put telomerase, we

192
00:11:18.468 --> 00:11:22.248
activated an oncogene, K-RAS, in the lung to see whether

193
00:11:22.748 --> 00:11:26.488
telomerase was influencing the natural history of the

194
00:11:26.548 --> 00:11:27.728
K-RAS induced tumors

195
00:11:28.568 --> 00:11:32.378
in this mouse model developed by the group of Mariano Barbacid at

196
00:11:32.668 --> 00:11:33.068
the CNIO.

197
00:11:34.028 --> 00:11:36.208
And you can see that the telomerase

198
00:11:37.048 --> 00:11:40.888
in the pre-treatment or simultaneous treatment models did not

199
00:11:40.928 --> 00:11:44.668
increase the number of mice with tumors, the tumors per

200
00:11:44.728 --> 00:11:46.188
mouse, or the tumor

201
00:11:47.048 --> 00:11:50.968
size. So telomerase was not actually changing

202
00:11:51.068 --> 00:11:53.988
the tumors induced by K-RAS in this model.

203
00:11:54.508 --> 00:11:54.928
Of course,

204
00:11:56.128 --> 00:11:59.568
humans are different, but at least in a mouse model where we are forcing lung

205
00:11:59.628 --> 00:12:02.468
cancer by inducing K-RAS mutation,

206
00:12:03.408 --> 00:12:07.098
telomerase is not altering theLet's say the number of

207
00:12:07.148 --> 00:12:11.128
tumors or the size of tumors indicating on the safety of the--

208
00:12:11.288 --> 00:12:14.808
I forgot to tell you, I will remind you that in the experiment I showed you

209
00:12:14.848 --> 00:12:18.408
before, where we treat mice with telomerase gene therapy, and we wait

210
00:12:18.608 --> 00:12:22.388
until all the mice die. Actually, cancer was delayed, and the mice lived

211
00:12:22.468 --> 00:12:25.888
longer. So again, showing that this strategy,

212
00:12:26.568 --> 00:12:30.508
with non-integrative, associated viruses, is not

213
00:12:30.588 --> 00:12:33.468
leading to more cancer, the expression of telomerase.

214
00:12:33.548 --> 00:12:37.508
So basically, we have shown that telomerase gene therapy can elongate

215
00:12:37.548 --> 00:12:41.348
lifespan in mice, slow down the progression of lung fibrosis, and

216
00:12:42.108 --> 00:12:45.828
we did not see more cancer in the lung when we forced the expression of

217
00:12:45.868 --> 00:12:49.848
K-RAS mutations in the lung. And we

218
00:12:49.928 --> 00:12:51.188
have now developed the

219
00:12:52.108 --> 00:12:53.308
human vectors, and

220
00:12:54.228 --> 00:12:58.148
I want to disclose that there is a company funded, which is called Telomere

221
00:12:58.188 --> 00:12:59.708
Therapeutics, that is trying to

222
00:13:00.588 --> 00:13:02.148
bring this to humans.

223
00:13:03.688 --> 00:13:06.648
So one important thing is to understand the role of

224
00:13:07.688 --> 00:13:10.988
the different mutations that are defined in the human patients.

225
00:13:11.028 --> 00:13:15.008
And I want to discuss one of the latest mutations found in patients of

226
00:13:15.068 --> 00:13:18.088
pulmonary fibrosis, which is in a telomere binding protein called POT1.

227
00:13:18.708 --> 00:13:22.568
I think POT1 is interesting because it's found mutated both in

228
00:13:22.588 --> 00:13:23.508
cancer and aging.

229
00:13:25.188 --> 00:13:28.608
So the same protein, which is a telomere binding protein important for telomerase

230
00:13:28.668 --> 00:13:32.608
activity at the telomeres, is found mutated in familial cases

231
00:13:32.628 --> 00:13:36.528
of cancer and familial cases of pulmonary fibrosis, which

232
00:13:36.548 --> 00:13:37.748
is an age-related disease.

233
00:13:39.148 --> 00:13:42.868
So in the case of the pulmonary fibrosis, we generated a mouse model,

234
00:13:43.228 --> 00:13:45.128
which is recapitulating this mutation,

235
00:13:46.228 --> 00:13:49.928
the human mutation in mice, and we see that the mutation leads to short

236
00:13:49.968 --> 00:13:50.518
telomeres,

237
00:13:52.128 --> 00:13:56.008
telomere fragility, which we measure by what we call the

