00:14:31.008 --> 00:14:32.308
generations of the POT1

250
00:14:33.248 --> 00:14:34.628
knock-in mouse model.

251
00:14:35.808 --> 00:14:39.188
Even the pathologies that we found in the telomerase knockout,

252
00:14:39.888 --> 00:14:41.148
which are characterized by

253
00:14:41.968 --> 00:14:43.368
small intestinal atrophy

254
00:14:44.188 --> 00:14:46.988
or testicular atrophy. You can see that

255
00:14:48.048 --> 00:14:51.748
in the third generation, POT1 knock-in and the third

256
00:14:51.768 --> 00:14:54.648
generation telomerase knockout, they are equivalent.

257
00:14:55.188 --> 00:14:55.548
So

258
00:14:56.428 --> 00:14:57.948
this mutation is acting like--

259
00:14:58.768 --> 00:15:00.068
I don't have time to show you, but

260
00:15:01.148 --> 00:15:04.368
if we overexpress telomerase in this POT1, it's not rescued in the short

261
00:15:04.388 --> 00:15:07.437
telomerase, so this mutation is acting as a dominant negative for telomerase.

262
00:15:07.548 --> 00:15:07.618
So,

263
00:15:10.488 --> 00:15:13.828
you can have a mutation in this telomere binding protein that is impeding the

264
00:15:13.888 --> 00:15:16.848
action of telomerase on the telomere, and that's why it's causing fibrosis.

265
00:15:16.908 --> 00:15:20.808
You will see that other mutations do exactly the opposite, and they are found in

266
00:15:20.848 --> 00:15:22.508
familiar cases of cancer.

267
00:15:24.308 --> 00:15:28.288
So another disease we have been studying is renal fibrosis, which

268
00:15:28.328 --> 00:15:31.888
is also very prevalent. And I don't have time to tell you the

269
00:15:31.928 --> 00:15:35.488
details, but my group has shown that short telomeres also lead

270
00:15:35.828 --> 00:15:39.508
to or are the origin of kidney fibrosis in mouse models.

271
00:15:40.328 --> 00:15:44.208
And in this particular case, we also discovered something unexpected, which

272
00:15:44.248 --> 00:15:47.888
is that short telomeres were sufficient to induce mesenchymal

273
00:15:47.948 --> 00:15:51.848
drift. So we found an epithelial to mesenchymal transition, which

274
00:15:51.888 --> 00:15:55.748
has been shown before to lead to kidney fibrosis, to be induced

275
00:15:56.468 --> 00:16:00.228
by short telomeres. And I think this is also very interesting

276
00:16:00.268 --> 00:16:03.428
because this mesenchymal transition is common to cancer and aging,

277
00:16:04.148 --> 00:16:05.497
and short telomeres can

278
00:16:06.468 --> 00:16:10.268
induce that. So it could be also the origin of this common aspect of cancer and

279
00:16:10.348 --> 00:16:10.608
aging,

280
00:16:11.408 --> 00:16:13.808
which is called mesenchymal drift.

281
00:16:15.768 --> 00:16:19.608
So the same as we did with the lung, we have identified the cell of origin of

282
00:16:19.628 --> 00:16:23.488
kidney fibrosis associated to dysfunctional telomeres, and it's not

283
00:16:23.527 --> 00:16:25.728
in the fibroblast or the pericytes.

284
00:16:26.188 --> 00:16:26.568
Only

285
00:16:27.888 --> 00:16:31.728
in very old mice we see some fibrosis when you induce telomere

286
00:16:31.768 --> 00:16:34.488
dysfunction in the fibroblast or the pericytes.

287
00:16:35.028 --> 00:16:38.988
However, when we induce telomere dysfunction in the renal tubular epithelial

288
00:16:39.068 --> 00:16:42.948
cells or the basal cells, again, the more regenerative compartments, the

289
00:16:42.988 --> 00:16:46.528
same as with the lung, we get fibrosis, a very severe

290
00:16:46.568 --> 00:16:50.498
fibrosis. So again, it's the short telomeres in the epithelial compartments or

291
00:16:50.548 --> 00:16:54.268
the basal compartments, the ones that are causing the fibrosis.

292
00:16:54.328 --> 00:16:57.708
And I think this is interesting because even though fibrosis is characterized

293
00:16:57.768 --> 00:16:58.488
by,

294
00:17:00.608 --> 00:17:02.538
let's say, activation of fibroblasts,

295
00:17:03.708 --> 00:17:07.348
it's when we induce telomere dysfunction in epithelial cells, when we get

296
00:17:07.449 --> 00:17:09.808
this fibrotic phenotype.

297
00:17:11.748 --> 00:17:14.048
And this is the part I wanted to tell you about

298
00:17:16.048 --> 00:17:18.568
aging, and I will now switch to

299
00:17:19.628 --> 00:17:20.028
cancer.

300
00:17:21.068 --> 00:17:24.949
You know this very famous review by Juan Berrahan-Hanahan, and one

301
00:17:25.008 --> 00:17:28.748
of the hallmarks of cancer is the ability of cancer cells to

302
00:17:28.768 --> 00:17:32.148
divide indefinitely. And as I mentioned before, they achieve this

303
00:17:32.748 --> 00:17:36.668
in 90% of the cases, more or less, by mutating

304
00:17:36.688 --> 00:17:40.638
telomerase. So telomerase activity is reactivated in tumors

305
00:17:41.228 --> 00:17:44.908
through mutations in promoters, amplification, et cetera, but not

306
00:17:44.948 --> 00:17:48.808
only telomerase. My group also was

307
00:17:49.568 --> 00:17:52.768
among the first groups that described mutations in shelterin,

308
00:17:53.688 --> 00:17:55.128
in familiar cases of cancer,

309
00:17:56.028 --> 00:17:59.548
and in particular, the first telomere binding protein found

310
00:17:59.588 --> 00:18:03.128
mutated, and I think is one of the few actually found mutated in cancer, is

311
00:18:03.228 --> 00:18:07.168
POT1. Again, the same one I told you before with pulmonary

312
00:18:07.188 --> 00:18:11.128
fibrosis. So we found that POT1 mutation,

313
00:18:11.248 --> 00:18:14.352
in this case, in the cancer caseleads to

314
00:18:15.512 --> 00:18:19.392
abnormally long telomeres. So the opposite to the mutation I told

315
00:18:19.432 --> 00:18:20.672
you for pulmonary fibrosis.

316
00:18:21.512 --> 00:18:24.972
And these abnormally long telomeres, however, are not normal.

317
00:18:25.312 --> 00:18:29.212
They are mutant for POT1, and this means that

318
00:18:29.252 --> 00:18:32.032
they are more fragile, I will show you.

319
00:18:33.172 --> 00:18:37.032
So these are long telomeres, it's true, but not normal long telomeres like the

320
00:18:37.072 --> 00:18:39.452
ones I showed you before with the chimeric mice.

321
00:18:40.492 --> 00:18:44.352
So we were the first one to describe these mutations in CLL, but then other groups

322
00:18:44.372 --> 00:18:48.042
have described this mutation in glioblastoma and other tumor types,

323
00:18:48.332 --> 00:18:51.332
other POT1 mutations. And we also found

324
00:18:52.292 --> 00:18:55.972
a POT1 mutation in Li-Fraumeni like syndrome,

325
00:18:56.392 --> 00:18:58.372
which is not associated to P53 mutations.

326
00:18:58.472 --> 00:19:02.192
So this is a Li-Fraumeni syndrome with many different tumors

327
00:19:02.272 --> 00:19:04.772
appearing in these families, including cardiac

328
00:19:05.732 --> 00:19:06.972
tumors, which are very rare.

329
00:19:08.392 --> 00:19:08.612
And

330
00:19:10.552 --> 00:19:14.292
later on, the group of Mery Armanios also found a POT1

331
00:19:14.372 --> 00:19:17.752
mutation in the cases of familial clonal hematopoiesis.

332
00:19:19.212 --> 00:19:22.532
And so confirming our results

333
00:19:22.812 --> 00:19:26.452
and showing that these abnormally long telomeres,

334
00:19:28.312 --> 00:19:29.812
associated POT1 mutations

335
00:19:31.412 --> 00:19:32.372
could be related to

336
00:19:33.512 --> 00:19:37.492
morigenic processes. But I want to make the emphasis is that

337
00:19:37.552 --> 00:19:41.472
a POT1 mutant telomere is not a normal telomere because it has

338
00:19:41.512 --> 00:19:42.392
mutations in POT1.

339
00:19:43.742 --> 00:19:47.712
So, this is some of the major tumor types where the mutations have

340
00:19:47.752 --> 00:19:51.412
been found, and we generated a mouse model also for this Li-Fraumeni like

341
00:19:51.932 --> 00:19:52.652
syndrome that we,

342
00:19:54.472 --> 00:19:58.452
together with a group of Manuel Benito, discovered at the Spanish National

343
00:19:58.512 --> 00:20:02.432
Cancer Center. And in this case, it's the opposite to the

344
00:20:02.452 --> 00:20:06.232
POT mutant I showed you before for pulmonary fibrosis, we get longer

345
00:20:06.292 --> 00:20:10.192
telomeres. In the case of the POT1 mutant, you can

346
00:20:10.272 --> 00:20:12.592
see this in the

347
00:20:14.392 --> 00:20:16.492
mutants compared to the wild types.

348
00:20:16.572 --> 00:20:19.662
The telomeres are longer, and they are also more

349
00:20:19.692 --> 00:20:23.612
fragile. And this is in MEFs and iPS, but

350
00:20:23.672 --> 00:20:26.512
also in different tissues. And the mice also develop

351
00:20:27.252 --> 00:20:28.312
angiosarcomas,

352
00:20:29.112 --> 00:20:30.672
similar to the

353
00:20:32.712 --> 00:20:34.532
human Li-Fraumeni like syndrome.

354
00:20:35.212 --> 00:20:36.272
And in this case,

355
00:20:37.152 --> 00:20:40.932
the mutant is not acting as a dominant negative as the one I showed you before,

356
00:20:42.152 --> 00:20:45.812
for the POT1 mutation in pulmonary fibrosis, but is acting as a

357
00:20:46.612 --> 00:20:50.332
processivity, let's say, increasing the processivity of telomerase.

358
00:20:51.372 --> 00:20:55.252
So what happens with this mutant is allowing for a lower inhibition

359
00:20:55.292 --> 00:20:59.132
of telomerase at the telomeres and a higher activity of telomerase at the

360
00:20:59.172 --> 00:21:02.712
telomeres. The opposite to the other mutant that is acting as a dominant

361
00:21:02.732 --> 00:21:03.232
negative.

362
00:21:04.552 --> 00:21:08.532
So I think it's important to study every different mutation because it can lead

363
00:21:08.592 --> 00:21:10.512
to very different phenotypes,

364
00:21:11.412 --> 00:21:13.872
even if it's in the same protein.

365
00:21:15.592 --> 00:21:18.832
So we have this ability of cancer cells to

366
00:21:19.952 --> 00:21:21.321
maintain telomeres. This is

367
00:21:22.912 --> 00:21:24.852
a hallmark of cancer, and

368
00:21:26.452 --> 00:21:27.792
telomerase inhibitors have been

369
00:21:29.052 --> 00:21:32.852
developed in the past. However, they have not been very successful, in part

370
00:21:32.892 --> 00:21:34.572
because there is a phenotypic lag.

371
00:21:34.672 --> 00:21:35.692
So a time

372
00:21:37.272 --> 00:21:41.172
between when you inhibit telomerase and achieving short telomeres, which

373
00:21:41.272 --> 00:21:43.512
probably is too long for some cancers.

374
00:21:43.992 --> 00:21:47.052
And also because some tumors can maintain telomeres by recombination.

375
00:21:47.172 --> 00:21:50.172
So inhibition of telomerase may not be that effective.

376
00:21:50.272 --> 00:21:54.072
So our idea was, instead of targeting telomerase, to

377
00:21:54.112 --> 00:21:57.692
target the telomere binding proteins, the sheltering proteins, which are the

378
00:21:57.732 --> 00:21:59.262
protective complex of the telomeres.

379
00:22:00.512 --> 00:22:04.332
And, the group of Tite de Langa, but also our group, have shown

380
00:22:04.372 --> 00:22:06.852
that all these proteins are essential for

381
00:22:07.852 --> 00:22:11.452
cell division except POT1. And in particular, we were

382
00:22:11.512 --> 00:22:13.072
interested in TRF1.

383
00:22:14.132 --> 00:22:17.952
When you delete TRF1 in the mice, you induce telomere dysfunction in

384
00:22:17.992 --> 00:22:20.632
every single chromosome end. So it's a

385
00:22:21.612 --> 00:22:24.612
persistent telomere damage, which is sufficient to stop cells.

386
00:22:25.792 --> 00:22:26.122
But TRF1,

387
00:22:28.092 --> 00:22:32.032
compared to the other shelterins, has another property that is important for

388
00:22:32.092 --> 00:22:35.041
stem cells, and my group has been doing work on that.

389
00:22:35.992 --> 00:22:39.972
It's overexpressed in pluripotent and adult stem cell

390
00:22:40.032 --> 00:22:43.972
compartments, and is essential to maintain pluripotency and stemness

391
00:22:43.992 --> 00:22:47.752
in adult cells. So we thought it could be a good target for a potential

392
00:22:49.372 --> 00:22:51.762
therapy targeting telomeres in cancer.

393
00:22:52.352 --> 00:22:55.202
And using mouse models, we have shown that this is effective,

394
00:22:56.612 --> 00:23:00.582
of course, in mouse models of lung cancer and also

395
00:23:00.592 --> 00:23:03.212
glioblastoma. We have shown the

396
00:23:04.752 --> 00:23:08.352
benefit of inhibiting TRF1 in these two cancer

397
00:23:08.392 --> 00:23:08.852
models.

398
00:23:09.792 --> 00:23:11.572
And we have seen that this is not

399
00:23:12.472 --> 00:23:15.692
too toxic. So if we

400
00:23:16.612 --> 00:23:18.832
delete TRF1 in the whole organism,

401
00:23:20.272 --> 00:23:23.912
in a wild type or P53 or P16 ARF

402
00:23:24.092 --> 00:23:27.552
mutant backgrounds, this is not changing dramatically the

403
00:23:27.612 --> 00:23:31.452
survival of the mice. So we of course get some phenotypes

404
00:23:31.632 --> 00:23:34.512
in the skin and the hair.

405
00:23:35.872 --> 00:23:36.132
But

406
00:23:37.132 --> 00:23:37.412
still,

407
00:23:38.412 --> 00:23:42.352
inhibition of TRF1 in the embryo is lethal, but in

408
00:23:42.392 --> 00:23:46.292
the adult, it's allowing for a therapeutic window, as you can see

409
00:23:46.352 --> 00:23:50.182
here. And we don't get more tumors in the case of the P16

410
00:23:51.892 --> 00:23:55.752
ARF or the P53 mutants, which was something that worried

411
00:23:55.772 --> 00:23:58.972
us. Maybe we inhibit TRF1 and we can stop

412
00:23:59.612 --> 00:24:03.152
cancer growth. But down the line, TRF1 is going to lead to chromosomal instability

413
00:24:03.172 --> 00:24:06.552
and secondary tumors. But this, in mouse models at least, doesn't seem to be the

414
00:24:06.592 --> 00:24:07.792
case. So this led us to

415
00:24:08.712 --> 00:24:11.972
start the screenings for small molecules that will be able to target

416
00:24:12.852 --> 00:24:16.172
telomeres. And we develop a knock-in

417
00:24:16.492 --> 00:24:20.352
mouse, where TRF1 is fused to

418
00:24:20.412 --> 00:24:24.272
GFP, and you have the telomeres green, and you can look for inhibitors

419
00:24:24.312 --> 00:24:28.232
that decrease the green fluorescence, which is the telomere binding

420
00:24:28.272 --> 00:24:29.212
protein TRF1.

421
00:24:30.192 --> 00:24:33.902
And we found-- Sorry.We

422
00:24:33.962 --> 00:24:34.322
found

423
00:24:35.282 --> 00:24:38.932
several molecules. We target deconvolute them, and we found

424
00:24:40.082 --> 00:24:43.302
something that we didn't know before, is that the

425
00:24:43.442 --> 00:24:47.282
PI3K/Akt pathway is

426
00:24:47.302 --> 00:24:50.842
important for TRF1 stability. So when you have

427
00:24:50.882 --> 00:24:54.422
inhibitors with PI3K/Akt, you

428
00:24:55.862 --> 00:24:59.742
decrease the amount of TRF1 at telomeres, and that's why these inhibitors are

429
00:25:02.182 --> 00:25:06.042
inhibiting TRF1. Then we found that TRF1 is phosphorylated, but

430
00:25:06.082 --> 00:25:06.742
by Akt.

431
00:25:07.822 --> 00:25:10.822
This is in the mouse, if you mutate this

432
00:25:11.762 --> 00:25:15.162
residue that is phosphorylated by Akt, you decrease TRF1

433
00:25:15.172 --> 00:25:17.442
phosphorylation. And this is important

434
00:25:19.002 --> 00:25:21.962
in vivo because it decreases TRF1 stability,

435
00:25:22.942 --> 00:25:26.082
decreases the binding to telomeric oligos,

436
00:25:26.802 --> 00:25:30.682
and when you try to reconstitute a telomerase-deficient cell with these

437
00:25:30.702 --> 00:25:33.142
mutants, they also fail to locate to the telomere.

438
00:25:33.202 --> 00:25:37.201
So this phosphorylation of TRF1 by Akt is important for TRF1 stability.

439
00:25:37.682 --> 00:25:41.482
This is in the mouse, but we found that human TRF1 is also phosphorylated by

440
00:25:41.562 --> 00:25:42.002
Akt,

441
00:25:42.922 --> 00:25:46.522
and if we generate a mutant in the phosphorylation site

442
00:25:47.982 --> 00:25:51.642
using this knock-in, using CRISPR-Cas in human

443
00:25:51.722 --> 00:25:55.002
cells, we see a

444
00:25:55.442 --> 00:25:57.602
decrease TRF1 levels,

445
00:25:58.842 --> 00:26:01.822
more DNA damage, and we also see

446
00:26:02.562 --> 00:26:04.882
decreased telomere length in the case of the human cells.

447
00:26:05.142 --> 00:26:08.682
So again, in TRF1 phosphorylation in human

448
00:26:08.802 --> 00:26:12.702
cells by Akt is important for TRF1 stability

449
00:26:12.942 --> 00:26:16.542
and for telomere length. Because we use a cancer cell line to do the

450
00:26:16.562 --> 00:26:20.262
knock-ins, we check also the ability of this cancer cell line

451
00:26:20.742 --> 00:26:24.542
to induce tumors. And you can see that the TRF1

452
00:26:24.642 --> 00:26:28.262
mutants that cannot be phosphorylated by Akt have

453
00:26:29.682 --> 00:26:32.502
a slower growth of tumor. So,

454
00:26:33.882 --> 00:26:37.652
this was very interesting for us because all this is telling us that in human and

455
00:26:37.702 --> 00:26:38.382
mouse cells,

456
00:26:41.162 --> 00:26:44.202
telomeres can be modified by the environment.

457
00:26:44.642 --> 00:26:46.362
So in this case, by the

458
00:26:46.802 --> 00:26:49.482
PI3K/Akt pathway. So

459
00:26:50.322 --> 00:26:54.162
the status of telomere protection can be altered by

460
00:26:55.162 --> 00:26:57.302
these pathways that respond to the

461
00:26:58.482 --> 00:27:01.362
environment. So I think this is very interesting.

462
00:27:02.502 --> 00:27:05.822
And actually what we did next is to screen for

463
00:27:06.782 --> 00:27:08.662
different FDA-approved drugs

464
00:27:09.482 --> 00:27:11.842
to see how many of them were targeting TRF1.

465
00:27:12.382 --> 00:27:15.382
If the telomere protection is important for cancer, and

466
00:27:16.222 --> 00:27:20.002
we are finding signaling pathways that regulate TRF1, maybe we will

467
00:27:20.102 --> 00:27:23.682
find other pathways that are important for telomere protection.

468
00:27:24.502 --> 00:27:28.382
And actually, we found that the PI3K/Akt pathway,

469
00:27:28.902 --> 00:27:31.642
but we also found the RAS pathway as an important pathway,

470
00:27:32.742 --> 00:27:34.522
regulating TRF1

471
00:27:35.902 --> 00:27:37.242
post-transcriptional regulation.

472
00:27:37.282 --> 00:27:41.002
And actually, you can see here the different phosphorylation sites that we have

473
00:27:41.062 --> 00:27:42.862
found in TRF1.

474
00:27:44.262 --> 00:27:46.902
And there is one particular site,

475
00:27:47.902 --> 00:27:51.482
threonine 330, that is phosphorylated by

476
00:27:51.802 --> 00:27:53.502
many different kinases,

477
00:27:54.322 --> 00:27:58.022
including the RAS, the mTOR, and the Akt pathway.

478
00:27:58.722 --> 00:28:01.642
So what we have done is to

479
00:28:02.202 --> 00:28:04.722
generate both phospho-mimetic and

480
00:28:06.342 --> 00:28:10.322
phospho-dead mutants in this site in mice to see the in

481
00:28:10.362 --> 00:28:14.302
vivo function of this mutation. So this is still unpublished, but we have

482
00:28:14.322 --> 00:28:17.662
generated mice knock-in for this particular site,

483
00:28:18.262 --> 00:28:21.122
which is phospho-dead or phospho-mimetic.

484
00:28:22.102 --> 00:28:23.482
And we see that the

485
00:28:24.802 --> 00:28:25.562
phospho-dead

486
00:28:26.602 --> 00:28:27.162
has a

487
00:28:28.942 --> 00:28:30.662
tendency to have lower TRF1.

488
00:28:31.962 --> 00:28:35.502
The phospho-mimetic has higher levels of TRF1, and this is

489
00:28:35.542 --> 00:28:38.542
correlated to a stability, to a half-life of TRF1.

490
00:28:38.662 --> 00:28:42.642
So the phospho-dead, as we saw in the case of the human

491
00:28:42.722 --> 00:28:46.042
cancer cells or in the case of the mouse

492
00:28:47.362 --> 00:28:47.822
cells,

493
00:28:49.282 --> 00:28:49.802
in vitro,

494
00:28:50.962 --> 00:28:54.722
there is less stability for TRF1, and the phospho-mimetic has a higher stability.

495
00:28:56.542 --> 00:29:00.522
We have seen also that the phospho-dead has shorter telomeres.

496
00:29:00.702 --> 00:29:02.382
In the mouse, these are MEFs.

497
00:29:03.442 --> 00:29:06.542
And this correlates with a higher presence of

498
00:29:07.082 --> 00:29:10.982
undetectable telomeres or signal-free ends, and the phospho-mimetic

499
00:29:11.042 --> 00:29:11.422
has,

500
00:29:13.762 --> 00:29:15.072
in this case, in

